[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing test class order**\n\nI'm looking at the current build report and wondering about the class order for tests. I’m thinking we could add a new test class or modify an existing one to make sure fallback works before the initialization. JUnit doesn't guarantee the order, but Gradle might influence it. If I add a test that starts with \"A,\" it could run first, but it seems tricky since naming requires a specific mapping. It's a bit complicated, but I need to ensure that everything initializes correctly.\n\n**Exploring initialization prevention**\n\nI'm considering whether I can prevent earlier initialization, but it seems challenging. I’m thinking about resetting the static DISPATCHER of the original NexusAccessor and invoking CreationAction.run through publicly accessible means, but tests outside the package can't access compiled code. I can use reflection to get around this, except reflection should generally be avoided unless absolutely necessary. If `CreationAction` implements PrivilegedAction, it complicates access since the type isn't publicly accessible. I need to test this mentally to check if it's feasible!\n\n**Considering access to protected members**\n\nI'm thinking about how protected members work in Java. They can be accessed within the same package or by subclasses, but my test is outside of that. I wonder if I could create a subclass of NexusAccessor to access those protected members. Since it's a static nested interface, I believe a subclass should be able to access the protected static member. It feels like a potential solution to gain the necessary access I need!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_07066c0709a9ed1a0169faadf992248190a23244dbd7b3fa01\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp-q4DFwl8rd1NaQrYHMPWJVLxMu_z5yhSQCyOxxcE6VJBqT4J8_j3XmxHbKBWIVtTBge7U48YSgde_tzwLtuuPOa_Q2HOvzSLvoVmkch7taB4PM3VLURLjxC9PxWBaFcBjJp